T
he exploration of chemical space is crucial for the creation of new virtual compounds. These virtual molecules hold immense potential ‚Äì
they could be the next generation of drug-like molecules, serving as the starting point for groundbreaking discoveries in drug
development. To achieve this goal, researchers have developed a variety of molecular generation tools. However, evaluating the
effectiveness of these generators presents a complex challenge.
Current evaluation methods primarily focus on technical aspects, ensuring a generated molecule is valid and unique. However, these
methods fail to consider the crucial factor of potential biological activity ‚Äì the ultimate goal in drug discovery.
This work proposes a novel approach to benchmarking chemical structure generators. We focus on scaffolds, the core
structure of a molecule, to identify biologically active patterns that the generator can discover even if they weren't part of the
training data. This allows us to assess a generator's ability to generate entirely new and potentially effective drug candidates.
The goal is to give scientists a better way to compare these generators, so they can find the ones that make the best virtual compounds
for life-saving drugs!
